, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume D' Esneval De Pavilly was born about 1220, in Scotland, his father, Robert II \"le Boiteux\" d'ESNEVAL, was 60 and his mother, Anne Crespin, was 42. He had at least 1 son with Ide de Mauvoisin de ROSNY. He died in 1319, in his hometown, at the age of 100."},"et":{"abt 1220–1319":"umbes 1220–1319","1220–1319":"1220–1319","1258–Female":"1258–Surnud","1249–Male":"1249–Surnud","1161–1242":"1161–1242","1179–Female":"1179–Surnud","1249":"1249","1258":"1258","1179":"1179","1242":"1242","1220":"1220","8 July 1249":"8. juuli 1249","abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1161":"1161","1319":"1319","October 1242":"oktoober 1242","Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Renfrewshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"abt 1220–1319":"noin 1220–1319","1220–1319":"1220–1319","1258–Female":"1258–Kuollut","1249–Male":"1249–Kuollut","1161–1242":"1161–1242","1179–Female"